===Etymology===
Modern Latin, from {{etyl|grc}} {{term|ἀφασία||sc=polytonic}}, from {{term|ἄφατος||speechless|sc=polytonic}}, from {{term|ἀ-||[[a-]]|sc=polytonic}} + {{term|φάσις||speech|sc=polytonic}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|/əˈfeɪzɪə/}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun|s|-}}

# {{pathology}} A [[partial]] or [[total]] [[loss]] of [[language]] [[skill]]s due to [[brain]] [[damage]]. Usually, damage to the left perisylvian region, including Broca's area and Wernike's area, causes aphasia.
#* '''1888''', Rudyard Kipling, ‘The Conversion of Aurelian McGoggin’, ''Plain Tales from the Hills'', Folio 2005, p. 76:
#*: The Doctor came over in three minutes, and heard the story.  ‘It's '''''aphasia''''',’ he said.

